Det Con Graeme Badcock said Swales had made the extravagant purchases at the expense of his employer.
"This was a lifestyle beyond his means," he said.
"There is a market for second hand stamps.
"If companies for example go out of business and they have a quantity of stamps that they want to get rid of there is an outlet to sell surplus stock.
"But, Mr Swales took advantage of that and saw an opportunity for himself to make some extra money.
"The stamp dealer sold the stamps at a value of 70% of their face value so for all Mr Swales stole he received about £60,000 through his bank accounts."
